/*navbar wraps four (4) tags [a div called center, my header, a div called links, and my <a> tags. By setting navbar's position to absolute, it becomes positioned relative to its parent, which is the body. I had to specify zero positioning at the top, right, and left in order to tighten the element to the edge of the browser*/
.navbar{
  font-size: 38px;
  background-color:#ffffff;
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  right: 0;
  left: 0;
  
}
/*one of the easiest tags to understand; note to self... I had to float this element left*/
header{
  color: #ffffff;
  border-color: #cccccc;
  font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif;
  float: left;
  background-color: #4aaaa5;
  padding: 10px;
}

/*center a content width of 960px by adjusting margins; i know how to use the margin shorthand, but I shall revsit this page to learn, and I am too new to practice this technique */
.center {
  margin-top: 0;
  margin-right: auto; 
  margin-bottom: 0; 
  margin-left: auto;
  width: 960px;
}

.image{
  position: relative;
  float:left;

}

#pic-tag{
  position:absolute;
}

/*I could have made my links a <ul><li>, but this worked well enough.  Ask Uzair or Jose the benefits of making a navbar menu an unordered list*/
.links{
  float: right;
  margin-top: 10px; 
}

/*this markup command rids each menu item from the underline (which was distracting.  By setting the color to hashtag, I eliminate the ugly default blue color of a link*/
a {color: #777;
  text-decoration: none;
  color: #;
 } 

/*notice how the margin of this container is set to auto. This mirrors the centering of the navbar above, and since both elements are set to a required width of 960px, the margin auto works on the left and right side to center everthing inside this selector.  The 100px is for the top and bottom ("I'm using shorthand slowly but surely!"*/
.container{
  width: 960px;
  margin: 100px auto;
  background-color:#ffffff;
  font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
  
}
/*this gives the word "Contact" a 20px margin, but I sense that this could have somehow been achieved within a parent element. Hummm? */
.title{
  margin: 20px;
}

/*Notice how my contact labes have draw themselves away from the white edges of the container element.*/
.forms {
  margin: 20px;
  color: #777;
}

/*without this instruction, the width of the rectangular input fields would have been very small -- default small.  The HW assignment required the rectangles to fit the entire width of the container, hence 100 percent. */
input{
  width: 100%;
}

/*I had orignially swapped the "color" and "background color" values, which yielded an inverse color sheme for the button. I stupidly paused at the simple task of swapping color values--but now I fully understand. */
